      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Application Scenarios</h2>
        <div class="scenario-list">
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Paper Roll Guide Rail Support in Converting Equipment</h3>
            <p>Paper roll guide rails in converting, printing, and packaging equipment must maintain precise lateral web guidance to prevent edge wandering and web breaks. The inner fixing plate provides the structural anchor for the guide rail, and its machined flatness and hole position accuracy determine whether the rail is mounted in the correct alignment. Dimensional errors in the fixing plate translate directly into web alignment problems that reduce production efficiency and product quality.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Web-Handling Equipment Frame Components</h3>
            <p>Web-handling equipment for film, foil, and paper applications requires structural plates that are flat, accurately drilled, and machined to consistent dimensions across multiple units in the same machine. The inner fixing plate that anchors the guide rail system must hold its dimensional relationship to the frame structure throughout the service life of the equipment under the vibration and tension loads of continuous web processing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Equipment Retrofit and Upgrade Components</h3>
            <p>When existing converting or printing equipment is upgraded to handle wider web widths or new material types, the guide rail support structure often requires new or modified inner fixing plates. CNC milling produces these retrofit components to the updated design drawings with the same accuracy as the original machine components, ensuring the upgraded equipment performs as designed.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Flatness and Hole Position: The Critical Dimensions</h2>
        <p>For guide rail fixing plates, the two most critical dimensional requirements are face flatness (which determines how well the rail seats against the plate) and bolt hole position accuracy (which determines whether the rail mounts in the correct position and remains aligned under load). Both are confirmed during our pre-shipment inspection. Send your drawing with flatness and position tolerances specified, and we will confirm achievable tolerances before committing to the order.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block faq-block">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What is the function of the inner fixing plate in a guide rail system?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">The inner fixing plate anchors the guide rail structure to the machine frame, providing the mounting surface that determines the guide rail's position and alignment. Its flatness, hole position accuracy, and structural integrity directly determine whether the guide rail maintains correct web alignment during production.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What materials are used for guide rail fixing plates?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Material is specified in the customer drawing. Aluminum alloy (6061 or 6063) is common for weight reduction in larger plates. Carbon steel or stainless steel is used where higher strength or corrosion resistance is required. Material selection advice is available if needed.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What flatness tolerance can you achieve for the plate face?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Face flatness achievable by CNC milling depends on the plate size and material. Typical flatness for aluminum plates under 500mm is 0.05mm or better. For larger plates or tighter requirements, contact us with your specification for a capability confirmation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Can you machine plates to custom dimensions?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. All precision milled plates are produced to customer drawings with no standard sizes. Provide the drawing with all critical dimensions, tolerances, and surface finish requirements for a quotation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Do you supply anodized aluminum plates?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. Anodizing is available for aluminum fixing plates for corrosion protection and improved surface hardness. Anodize type (Type II or Type III) and color are specified at the order stage.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What is the typical lead time?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Lead time depends on plate complexity, size, and quantity. Prototype quantities typically take 7–15 working days. Batch production lead times are confirmed at quotation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

